  "dateModified": "2026-03-06",
  "datePublished": "2026-03-06",
  "description": "A substrate is the material that a fungus grows on, in, and through — the physical medium that provides both structural support and nutrition. For saprotrophic fungi, the substrate is dead organic matter: a fallen log, a pile of leaf litter, a bed of wood chips, a bale of straw. For mycorrhizal fungi, the substrate is soil, with the plant root serving as a carbon source. For parasitic fungi, the substrate may be living tissue — a tree trunk, an insect body, a human lung.\n",
  "keywords": "mycology, ecology, nutrition",
  "name": "Substrate",
